HOSTNAME(1)                      User Commands                     HOSTNAME(1)

NAME
       hostname - show or set the system hostname

SYNOPSIS
       hostname [-adfhinsVvy] [-F file] [hostname]

DESCRIPTION
       Hostname is used to display the system's DNS name, and to display
       or set its hostname.  When called without any arguments, the
       program displays the current hostname.

       When called with one argument or with the -F option, the hostname
       is set to the specified value.  Only the superuser can set the
       hostname.

       Note that the hostname is usually set once at system startup by
       reading the contents of a file or by a DHCP client.

OPTIONS
       -a, --alias
              Display the alias name of the host (if used). This option
              is provided for compatibility; on LikeOS this displays the
              same as the hostname.

       -d, --domain
              Display the DNS domain name. This is the part after the
              first dot in the FQDN.

       -f, --fqdn, --long
              Display the FQDN (Fully Qualified Domain Name). A FQDN
              consists of the short hostname and the DNS domain name,
              separated by a dot.

       -F, --file FILE
              Read the hostname to be set from the specified FILE.
              Comments (lines starting with '#') are ignored.

       -h, --help
              Display usage information and exit.

       -i, --ip-address
              Display the network address(es) of the hostname. Note
              that this only works if the hostname can be resolved.

       -I, --all-ip-addresses
              Display all network addresses of the host. This enumerates
              all configured addresses on all network interfaces. The
              loopback interface and IPv6 link-local addresses are
              omitted.

       -n, --node
              Display the DECnet node name. On LikeOS this is the same
              as the hostname (provided for compatibility).

       -s, --short
              Display the short hostname. This is the hostname cut at
              the first dot.

       -v, --verbose
              Be verbose and tell what's going on.

       -V, --version
              Print version information on standard output and exit
              successfully.

       -y, --yp, --nis
              Display the NIS/YP domain name. If a parameter is given,
              root can also set a new NIS domain (not supported on
              LikeOS).

EXAMPLES
       hostname
              Display the current hostname.

       hostname myhost
              Set the hostname to "myhost".

       hostname -f
              Display the fully qualified domain name.

       hostname -F /etc/hostname
              Set the hostname by reading it from /etc/hostname.

       hostname -i
              Display the IP address associated with the hostname.

       hostname -I
              Display all configured IP addresses.

SEE ALSO
       uname(1), ifconfig(8)

